I recall the next time it happened, running to zone, shouting all the way, with a bub of health left.  Maybe you are some sort of superman who never has to run from a battle.  More likely not.  More likely you complain about things that inconvenience you, or cause you to have to think about where you're fighting and what you have to worry about in zone.  Whining about trains in crushbone is akin to complaining about the fact that you stood on the walkway in unrest and someone trained a skeletal monk on your butt (not saying you did, here, but the analogy carries).  Trains in crushbone happen.  Constantly.  And the fact that you chose to whine about it rather than finding a good strategy said volumes about your attitude.<br>
<br>
The lovely thing about grouping with Calare is the fact that she sits right next to me in RL.  I just have to look to my left to see what's happening on her screen.  I watched you train Calare and our companion.  I saw our companion's tell to Calare about your 'ha ha now you know how it feels' tell.  I saw his confirmation after we told him how to report you correctly.  I also recall, shortly thereafter, you casting shield of brambles on me (I assumed it was an 'I'm sorry' gesture but at the time I just wanted your blood, so I killed the effect).<br>
<br>
So I stand by what I said.  You are a sanctimonious schmoe who whines, and when you're finished whining you participate in just the activities you've been whining about if it suits your needs.<br>
<br>
Note:<br>
<br>
-Hey, Order of the Oaken is holding a spawn when _I_ don't think they should be allowed to.<br>
-Hey everyone, gather around me in support.<br>
-In retaliation, let's grab and hold the spawn for two days.<br>
<br>
Don't you notice the hipocricy of this?  You could argue that you were doing it for the greater good, but that wouldn't be true, would it.  You did it because you think percieved wrongs justify any actions.<br>
<br>
I should point out here, that many people run into many problems and percieve that they've been wronged.  Happens to Calare and I all the time.  Now, we _could_ dive on the boards and whine about it, and try to get everyone to say &quot;oh dear, you are so right!&quot; and &quot;that's horrible, here's a bottle!&quot; but that only serves to belittle the whiner.  Even if it does give you a quick, cheap ego boost.  Instead, we suck it up, adjust our tactics to take unforseen variables into account, and dive back in with a more refined method.  This way we become more effective at what we do, and we see that as a good thing.<br>
<br>
Fact of the matter is, trains happen.  Complain about them all you want, but it won't change that fact.  And you will no doubt cause your share throughout your career.  As well, when going after a rare spawn, disagreements will happen.  You handled the disagreement on that spawn wonderfully, and if not for the actions afterward, I would have said you had gained a world of respect in my eyes.  Fact of the matter is that I've done just the same thing in the past... pulled down a contested spawn (Moltor, in my case), then had someone pop in yelling about how they went LD and lost the kill, and just handed over the ring for the Paw of Opalla (heh, got calare plenty mad at me when I did that, but she later agreed).  However, running around and whining about it later (i.e., being sanctimonious), and then organizing a demonstration of just the kind of behavior that you've been whining about (i.e., being a schmoe)?  Sorry, but you've dropped back down to Saurek Rockhopper in my esteem.<br>
<br>
But I'm sure my esteem means nothing to you, as it should.  Your sanctimony will keep you bouyed all by itself.  And you can always find people to pity you if you complain loud enough... that should help the old ego too, huh?  And let's not forget... you can justify any action if you label it 'for the greater good'.<br>
<br>
Have fun being a martyr.  Just follow through and die in the process, ok? <p>Denoi<BR>
Taruun of Shar Val<BR><BR>

